description: From un- (“absence of, lack of”) +‎ sense.

entries.meaning: Lack or absence of sense; senselessness; nonsense.
examples: It is a matter of pressing to the threshold of sense, where unsense is simply the nascent becoming-sense of sense  […]

description: From un- (“reversal, removal”) +‎ sense. Distant cognate with German entsinnen (“to reflect”).

verbs.description: unsense (third-person singular simple present unsenses, present participle unsensing, simple past and past participle unsensed)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To remove or deprive of the senses; cause to be insensible.
